{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem requires finding a sequence of sibling merges to transform one tree into another. This involves identifying which nodes in the initial tree must be merged to match the structure and node values of the final tree, and then ordering those merges such that they are always performed on existing siblings.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "tree_structure_analyzer",
      "instructions": "Analyze the initial tree and the final tree to identify the specific sets of sibling nodes in the initial tree that must be merged to form each node in the final tree. For each node in the final tree, identify its parent in the final tree and determine which nodes in the initial tree correspond to it. Specifically, for every node in the final tree, find the set of nodes in the initial tree that are descendants of the same parent and must be merged together to result in that specific final node. Output a mapping where each final node is associated with a list of initial nodes that compose it."
    },
    {
      "label": "merge_sequence_generator",
      "instructions": "Given the mapping of final nodes to sets of initial nodes, generate a valid sequence of merge operations. A merge operation consists of picking two siblings in the current tree and merging them. To ensure validity, the sequence must be constructed such that a merge only occurs between nodes that are currently siblings. Use the mapping provided by the analyzer to identify which nodes need to be merged. A safe strategy is to process the tree from the leaves up to the root, or to ensure that for any set of nodes to be merged, we perform merges one by one among the siblings. Output the total number of merges followed by the pairs of node values to be merged."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent will take the mapping from the tree_structure_analyzer, which identifies which initial nodes must be combined to form each final node. The parent will then pass this structural information to the merge_sequence_generator to produce a valid, step-by-step sequence of sibling merges. The final output will be the formatted list of merge operations as required by the problem specification."
}

